# Job Search — <YOUR NAME>

This is your **profile and grounding corpus** — the single source of truth JobKit reads before it
tailors a resume, writes a cover letter, or preps you for an interview. The slash commands
(`/tailor`, `/prep`, `/log`, `/intake`) read this file. Everything they produce is grounded in what
you put here; if a fact isn't here (or in the base resumes under `resumes/`), the agent will not use
it. Fill it in honestly — accuracy here is what keeps the output from hallucinating.

> **How to fill this in:** the fastest path is the **Setup tab** in the JobKit UI (or run
> `/onboard` in the terminal) and paste your CV / LinkedIn text — the agent drafts this whole file
> for you. Then review and tighten every section. You can also fill it in by hand using the guidance
> below. Replace every `<...>` placeholder. Delete guidance lines (the `>` blockquotes) once done, or
> leave them — the agent ignores them.

---

## Snapshot
> One tight block of identity facts. The `/tailor` name + contact lines come straight from here.
- <Your Name> — <City, Country>. <Work authorisation / visa / right-to-work, if relevant>.
- <phone> · <email> · <linkedin.com/in/you>
- <Highest degrees, e.g. BSc Computer Science (Uni), MSc … (Uni)>. <N>+ years.
- Currently <exact job title> at <Company> (<start>–present).
- Languages: <language (level), language (level)> — state honest levels only.

## Positioning
> Who you are in one or two sentences, and how that flexes per role. Lead with your strongest
> identity; name the secondary framings a JD might call for.
- Core identity: <e.g. "Engineering Manager whose domain is X">.
- Framing A (<role type>): foreground <themes>.
- Framing B (<role type>): foreground <themes>.
- Do NOT present as <a framing that isn't really you>.

## Status / framing
> How to present your situation. These rules are honoured by /tailor and /prep.
- Present as currently <employed at X / open to work / …>. Never "ex-" or "former" if still there.
- Notice period / availability: <how to handle it — e.g. "don't raise notice unless asked directly">.
- Compensation: <your target / market range, or "competitive for the market"> — used as the /prep anchor.
- Search strategy: <selective / wide; timeframe>.

## Professional experience (titles are FIXED facts)
> List every role you'd put on a resume, most recent first. The exact title here is locked — /tailor
> will never upgrade or invent a different title. Add a one-line factual descriptor of each employer.
- **<Exact title>** — <Company> (<start>–<end or Present>), <location>. *<one-line: what the company does>*
- **<Exact title>** — <Company> (<dates>), <location>. *<descriptor>*
- **<Exact title>** — <Company> (<dates>), <location>. *<descriptor>*

## Achievement bank (facts — use, don't invent beyond these)
> The heart of the corpus. Every concrete, verifiable accomplishment — with real metrics, tools, and
> scope. Resume bullets are drawn ONLY from here (or your base resumes). Be specific: numbers, named
> systems, technologies. The richer and more honest this is, the better every tailor gets.
> Example shape (replace with your own):
> - Led <scope: N teams / N services / N markets> doing <what>, achieving <metric>.
> - Built <named system/tool>: <stack> — <impact, with a number>.
> - <Hard, quantified win with the real tools named>.
- <your achievement>
- <your achievement>
- <your achievement>

### Stack
> Your real tools/languages/platforms, grouped. Only what you've genuinely used — /tailor reorders
> these per JD but never adds a tool that isn't here.
- Languages: <…>
- Platforms / cloud: <…>
- <other relevant categories: testing, CI/CD, data, observability, …>

### Selected projects / beyond the day job (optional)
> Side projects, open source, portfolio pieces worth a line on a resume. Note honesty guardrails
> (solo vs team, prototype vs production) so they're never inflated.
- <project> — <one honest line>.

## Target companies (tiers) (optional)
- Dream: <…>
- Strong fit: <…>
- Solid: <…>

## Voice rules
> How your written materials should sound. The agent follows these for tone.
- Resume: <e.g. crisp, metric-led>. Cover letter: <e.g. warm but professional>.
- InMail: <constraints, e.g. <100 words, direct>.
- Never use: <banned words/buzzwords>. Spelling: <British/EU or US>.

## Apply / skip filter
> The honest bar for whether a role is worth applying to. /tailor's verdict uses this. Be willing to
> say SKIP.
Strong fit if MOST hold: <criterion>, <criterion>, comp >= <number/range>, location <…>. Miss two or
more → recommend SKIP and say why. Don't pad a weak fit.

## Honesty rules
- If a JD wants something you lack (a language, a specific domain), say so and suggest how to address
  it or whether to skip. Never fabricate experience to close a gap.
- Never invent a title, competency label, or skill that isn't in this file or the base resumes.
- ATS / keyword score is never a justification for adding something untrue — name the gap instead.

## Fabrication log
> Specific phrasings, titles, or claims the agent must NEVER use about you — things that read well but
> aren't true, or framings you've decided are off-limits. This grows as you catch and reject bad
> output. /tailor reads this before drafting and treats everything here as banned.
- Do NOT claim "<umbrella term you only partly have>" — you have <the real, narrower thing> only.
- Do NOT title <role> anything other than "<exact title>".
- <add entries here as you catch them>

## Tailoring lessons (learned from submitted resumes — grows over time)
> Generalisable framing/positioning lessons extracted from resumes you actually submitted. JobKit's
> learning loop appends approved lessons here automatically; /tailor reads them so each application is
> sharper than the last. Start empty.
- <appended over time>

